    "image_with_text_aG87DC": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "heading_6XRWbk": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Sharpening Basics",
            "heading_fs": "h3"
          }
        },
        "sub_heading_wxmcGg": {
          "type": "sub_heading",
          "settings": {
            "sub_heading": "The game is constantly evolving. High-level players in the NHL and other leagues are always changing up their game and gear just to find that little extra edge they can have on their opponents. One of the easiest ways to have that edge is by having a blade cut and profile that fits you, your environment, and your playstyle.<br><br>\n\nSkate sharpening may seem like just simple maintenance, but there is actually quite a bit more going into it than fixing edges.. Sure, you can play in any cut or profile as long as the edges are sharp and even and the finish is smooth. However, if the specs don’t agree with you, it’ll be difficult to reach your highest potential.<br><br> \n\nSharpening is measured on a scale. Deeper hollows will offer better traction on the ice and enhanced agility, whereas shallower hollows will offer better glide and more speed.",
            "sub_fs": "lg"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "heading_6XRWbk",
        "sub_heading_wxmcGg"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "image": "shopify:\/\/shop_images\/4th.jpg",
        "style_image": "1",
        "image_effect": "lunc",
        "color_scheme": "",
        "image_last": false,
        "content_position": "center",
        "alignment": "center",
        "content_pl": 0,
        "image_last_mb": false,
        "content_position_mb": "center",
        "alignment_mb": "center",
        "padding_top": 40,
        "padding_bottom": 40,
        "padding_rate": 75
      }
    },
    "image_with_text_8BYNEy": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "sub_heading_GRTFdX": {
          "type": "sub_heading",
          "settings": {
            "sub_heading": "A common misconception is that blades may seem “sharper” or “duller” after sharpening; in actuality, a “sharper” blade just means the cut was <b>deep<\/b>, and likewise, a “duller” blade means the cut was <b>shallow<\/b>. If you switch from 1\/2” to 5\/8” for example, you may initially think the blades weren’t sharpened well enough, but you’ve really just switched to a shallower cut.<br><br>\n\nThe Hockey Shop can help. Here's a full menu of sharpening options we offer:<br><br>\n\nBlademaster – Traditional Hollow, or ROH<br>\nBlademaster – Flat Bottom Hollow (Blade Form Dressing, or BFD)<br>\nBlackstone – Flat Bottom V (FBV)\nPro-Sharp – Z-Channel<br>\nSparx – Traditional Hollow, or RO",
            "sub_fs": "lg"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "sub_heading_GRTFdX"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "image": "shopify:\/\/shop_images\/DSCF0168.jpg",
        "style_image": "1",
        "image_effect": "lunc",
        "color_scheme": "",
        "image_last": true,
        "content_position": "center",
        "alignment": "center",
        "content_pl": 0,
        "image_last_mb": false,
        "content_position_mb": "center",
        "alignment_mb": "center",
        "padding_top": 40,
        "padding_bottom": 40,
